data.title: National Museum of American History
data.meta_description: Charles Edouard Guillaume was a Swiss metallurgist working at the International Bureau of Weights and Measures in Paris who, in 1896, found that a nickel-steel alloy (with about 35 per cent nickel) has a very small coefficient of expansion.
